! conclusion:
  When using design patterns as agent governance, teach agents to maintain pattern quality by promoting evidence and updating core reasoning

  + context: You are using flexiarg patterns as a control layer for agential coding infrastructure.
  + IF:
    Patterns guide agent behavior through IF/HOWEVER/THEN/BECAUSE reasoning and accumulate evidence in EVIDENCE/NEXT-STEPS sections

  + HOWEVER:
    Agents don't automatically know to maintain patterns ‚Äî they may treat patterns as write-only logs, appending evidence without updating core reasoning or promoting next-steps to evidence when completed

  + THEN:
    Explicitly teach agents pattern hygiene: (1) move completed NEXT-STEPS to EVIDENCE when done, (2) update core IF/HOWEVER/THEN/BECAUSE if evidence refutes or refines the reasoning, (3) prune obsolete next-steps, (4) mark patterns for promotion (:stub‚Üí:greenfield‚Üí:active‚Üí:settled) when criteria met

  + BECAUSE:
    Patterns can increase in quality through use and become living documents that reflect learned experience, rather than degrading into unmaintained dumping grounds. This keeps the library curated and trustworthy.

  + EVIDENCE:
    evidence[2026-01-22: During futon3a.devmap review, Joe spotted that P3 (Meme Layer) had dependency direction wrong and P2 (Compass) was missing prior art from futon2/fulab. These were fixed by updating EVIDENCE section and refining BECAUSE clause ‚Äî pattern improved through review]
    evidence[library/control patterns themselves model this: effort-estimation, agential-oss-infrastructure, agential-efficiency-measurement were created when meta-patterns became clear during devmap work]

  + NEXT-STEPS:
